{
  "name": "basal_ganglia",
  "description": "Minimal basal ganglia — action selection via disinhibition. Real basal ganglia: direct pathway (D1 striatum → GPi inhibit → thalamus disinhibit = GO) vs indirect pathway (D2 striatum → GPe inhibit → STN disinhibit → GPi excite = NO-GO). Dopamine tips the balance: D1 facilitated, D2 suppressed. Our version: 2 RS cortical inputs feed both D1 (RS, GO) and D2 (RS, NO-GO) striatal neurons via PLASTIC synapses. FS GPi tonically fires (self-excitation) and inhibits RS thalamus output. D1 inhibits GPi (disinhibits output = GO). D2 inhibits FS GPe, which normally inhibits RS STN. STN disinhibited excites GPi (strengthens NO-GO). CH dopamine facilitates D1 and suppresses D2. LTS provides tonic drive to maintain GPi baseline. Result: dopamine shifts selection toward GO. STDP on cortical→striatum learns which inputs to select. Implements: action selection, reinforcement learning, habit formation, response inhibition.",
